{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651078"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:19:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:19:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18430"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18430"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11148"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79496"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11148"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18430"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64818"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10260"},{"type":"tags","id":"10264"},{"type":"tags","id":"10265"},{"type":"tags","id":"11266"},{"type":"tags","id":"11267"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25833"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25836"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79496"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of knee pain following a minor sprain. She is an avid runner and is eager to return to her training routine. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The knee is stable with no swelling, but there is mild tenderness over the patellar tendon. The physiotherapist recommends exercises that involve muscle contraction without joint movement to help maintain strength while avoiding further injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of muscle contraction is being described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Isometric contraction","Isotonic contraction","Eccentric contraction","Concentric contraction","Plyometric contraction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe physiotherapist is recommending exercises that involve muscle contraction without joint movement, which is characteristic of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eisometric contraction\u003C/strong\u003E. In isometric exercises, the muscle generates force without changing its length, making it ideal for maintaining strength without stressing the joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsotonic contraction\u003C/strong\u003E involves muscle contraction with movement in which there is a change in muscle length, such as in weight lifting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConcentric contraction\u003C/strong\u003E is a type of isotonic contraction where there is muscle shortening during contraction, this is when lifting a dumbbell during a bicep curl.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEccentric contraction\u003C/strong\u003E is another type of isotonic contraction where there is muscle lengthening during contraction, such as is seen when lowering a weight slowly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlyometric contraction\u003C/strong\u003E involves the rapid stretching and contracting of muscles, this is typically used in explosive movements like jumping.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Isometric contraction occurs when a muscle generates force without changing length.","Isometric exercises are useful for maintaining muscle strength without joint movement.","Isometric contractions are often used in rehabilitation settings to prevent joint stress."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Longo, U. G., \u0026 Denaro, V. (Eds.). (2023). Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature","Hughes, S. H. (2022). The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95. doi: 10.1007/s00223-014-9915-y. Epub 2014 Oct 8. PMID: 25294644","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418. doi: 10.1055/s-0036-1586263. Epub 2016 Sep 23. PMID: 27704495"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64818"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18430"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64818"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T20:21:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T20:22:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11148"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79496"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medica